{{Multiple Issues | Refs Needed = June 2023 | Single Source = June 2023 }} {{Infobox ancient site|type = [[Zenpokoenfun]] |name = Kōshinzuka Kofun |image = [[File:庚申塚古墳１.jpg|250px|Full view of Kōshinzuka Kofun]] |location = {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県}}{{ill|Iizuna Town|ja|飯綱町}} Hirade, Nishinura 1007-1, 1008-1 |location = {{coord|36|43|22|N|138|15|01|E|map_size:20000}} |type = {{ill|Keyhole-shaped Kofun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun}} |built = Early {{ill|5th century|ja|5世紀}} |area = Total length: approx. 52m; Rear circle diameter: approx. 31m |Buried Person = Unknown |burial goods = Gri11ed {{ill|Haniwa|ja|埴輪}} ({{ill|Cylindrical Haniwa|ja|円筒埴輪|1=Cylindrical Haniwa}}) |Historic Site designation1 = Town (typeerly village) Historic Site1 in [[1980]] (Showa 55) }} '''Kōshinzuka Kofun''' (庚申塚古墳) is a {{ill|Keyhole-shaped Kofun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun}} located in {{ill|Iizuna Town|ja|飯綱町}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県}}.
The mound is named "Kōshinzuka" because an ancient {{ill|Kōshin-tō|ja|庚申塔}} was enshrined on it. In [[1933]] (Showa 8), Eiji Kuriiwa conducted an investigation and identified the site as a keyhole-shaped Kofun.
The mound, believed to have been constructed in the early {{ill|5th century|ja|5世紀}}, yielded burial goods including gri11ed {{ill|Haniwa|ja|埴輪}} (cylindrical Haniwa), marking it as the sixth example of such finds in Japan.
== Overview ==
* type: {{ill|Keyhole-shaped Kofun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun}} * area: ** Total length: approx. 52m ** Rear circle diameter: approx. 31m ** Rear circle height: 3.5m ** Front projection width: approx. 15–17m ** Front projection height: 1.5m
